Scala's collections library is one of the best reasons to use the language. It is large, but it is organized around a few clear ideas, and once you see them the whole thing becomes easy to navigate.

Start with the family. At the top sits a single abstraction, Iterable, anything you can step through one element at a time. Below it branch the three shapes you will actually reach for. A Seq is an ordered sequence, elements in a definite position, like a list. A Set is a collection of unique elements, with no duplicates and no guaranteed order. And a Map is a collection of key-to-value pairs, where you look things up by key. Almost every collection you touch is one of these three, and because they all share the Iterable interface, they also share a huge amount of behavior.

Now, which concrete type do you pick? Look at the choices. List is an immutable linked list. It is fast to add to the front and fast to take apart from the front, which makes it the natural fit for recursive, head-and-tail style code. Vector is an immutable indexed sequence with good performance everywhere, fast random access, fast updates, fast appends. When you are not sure, Vector is the safe default. Array is the low-level option: a fixed-size, mutable sequence backed directly by the JVM, which you reach for when you need raw performance or Java interop. Set gives you uniqueness; notice that Set of one, two, two collapses to just one and two. And Map gives you key-value lookup, built with the arrow syntax, key arrow value.

Here is the single most important property to internalize: Scala collections are immutable by default. When you import nothing special, List, Vector, Set, and Map all refer to immutable versions. An immutable collection can never change after you create it. So every operation that looks like it modifies the collection actually returns a brand-new one and leaves the original untouched. Watch: xs appended with four gives you a new list, one two three four, but xs itself is still one two three. Nothing was mutated.

You might worry that copying collections all the time would be slow. It is not, and the reason is structural sharing. Immutable collections are built as persistent data structures: the new version shares almost all of its internal structure with the old one, and only the differing part is new. So making a modified copy is cheap, often constant or logarithmic time, not a full duplication. You get the safety of immutability without paying for it.

Now the payoff that ties everything together: the transformation API. Because all of these collections share the Iterable interface, they share one uniform vocabulary of higher-order methods, and you learn it exactly once. Take a list of numbers. Map applies a function to every element and gives back a collection of the results, so map of underscore times two doubles them all. Filter keeps only the elements that satisfy a predicate, so filter of underscore mod two equals zero keeps the evens. Reduce combines all the elements pairwise into a single value, so reduce of plus sums them. FoldLeft is reduce with a starting seed, foldLeft of zero, then plus, which is safer because it works even on an empty collection. FlatMap maps each element to a collection and then flattens the results into one, which is how nested for-comprehensions desugar under the hood. And groupBy splits a collection into a Map, keyed by whatever function you give it, so groupBy of underscore mod two partitions the numbers into evens and odds.

Here is the beautiful part. Every one of those methods, map, filter, reduce, fold, flatMap, groupBy, works identically on a List, a Vector, a Set, or a Map. Learn the vocabulary once on a list, and you can transform any collection in the library the same way. And because these methods return new collections, you can chain them: filter, then map, then groupBy, each step a small honest transformation, exactly the functional style from the previous reel applied to real data.

So the whole library comes down to this. Pick a shape, Seq, Set, or Map. Pick a concrete type for your performance needs, usually List or Vector. Trust that it is immutable and cheap to copy. And then reach for the same uniform set of transformations every single time.
